Of course. As an SRE/DevOps expert, I can provide you with the AWS CLI command and a sample configuration file to create a CloudFront distribution with an S3 bucket as the origin.

The AWS CLI command to create a CloudFront distribution is `create-distribution`. This command requires a JSON file that contains all the configuration details for the distribution.

### AWS CLI Command

You will use the following command structure. You must first create the JSON configuration file and then reference it using the `--distribution-config` parameter.

```bash
aws cloudfront create-distribution --distribution-config file://distribution-config.json
```

### Example `distribution-config.json` File

Here is a basic example of a `distribution-config.json` file. This configuration sets up a CloudFront distribution that serves content from an S3 bucket.

Save the following content to a file named `distribution-config.json`.

```json
{
    "Comment": "My S3 static content distribution",
    "CallerReference": "your-unique-caller-reference-20260119",
    "Enabled": true,
    "Origins": {
        "Quantity": 1,
        "Items": [
            {
                "Id": "S3-my-static-website-bucket",
                "DomainName": "your-bucket-name.s3.amazonaws.com",
                "S3OriginConfig": {
                    "OriginAccessIdentity": ""
                }
            }
        ]
    },
    "DefaultCacheBehavior": {
        "TargetOriginId": "S3-my-static-website-bucket",
        "ViewerProtocolPolicy": "redirect-to-https",
        "TrustedSigners": {
            "Enabled": false,
            "Quantity": 0
        },
        "ForwardedValues": {
            "QueryString": false,
            "Cookies": {
                "Forward": "none"
            }
        },
        "MinTTL": 0,
        "AllowedMethods": {
            "Quantity": 2,
            "Items": [
                "GET",
                "HEAD"
            ],
            "CachedMethods": {
                "Quantity": 2,
                "Items": [
                    "GET",
                    "HEAD"
                ]
            }
        }
    },
    "DefaultRootObject": "index.html"
}
```

### Explanation of Key Configuration Fields

Before running the command, you need to update the following placeholders in the JSON file:

*   `"CallerReference"`: This must be a unique string for each `create-distribution` request. A timestamp or a UUID is a good choice. It prevents you from accidentally creating the same distribution twice.
*   `"DomainName"`: Replace `your-bucket-name.s3.amazonaws.com` with the actual domain name of your S3 bucket.
*   `"Id"` and `"TargetOriginId"`: These values link the cache behavior to the origin. `S3-my-static-website-bucket` is a descriptive ID you create. The `TargetOriginId` in `DefaultCacheBehavior` must match the `Id` in the `Origins` item.
*   `"S3OriginConfig"`: In this basic example, `"OriginAccessIdentity": ""` assumes your S3 bucket objects are publicly readable. For a more secure setup where the S3 bucket is private, you would create an Origin Access Identity (OAI) and specify its ID here (e.g., `"origin-access-identity/cloudfront/E1234567890ABC"`).
*   `"ViewerProtocolPolicy"`: Set to `"redirect-to-https"` to enforce HTTPS, which is a best practice.
*   `"DefaultRootObject"`: This is the file CloudFront will request from your origin when a viewer requests the root URL of your distribution (e.g., `https://d111111abcdef8.cloudfront.net/`).

After customizing and saving your `distribution-config.json` file, you can run the `aws cloudfront create-distribution` command shown above to create your distribution.
